est\nConduct comprehensive foundational research on customer behavioral patterns for the specified brand context. Focus on identifying measurable, predictable behavioral sequences that can form the basis for automated brand response systems.\n\n## Brand Characterization\nComplete this section for each research request:\n- **Brand Type:** {{B2B, B2C or Hybrid?}}  \n- **Industry:** {{Specific industry sector}}  \n- **Target Audience:** {{Primary customer demographic/psychographic profile}}  \n- **Business Model:** {{E-commerce, SaaS/, Service, Product or Marketplace?}}  \n- **Customer Lifecycle Stage Focus:** {{Acquisition, Engagement, Retention or Advocacy?}}  \n- **Geographic Scope:** {{Local, Regional, National or Global?}}  \n- **Digital Maturity:** {{Traditional, Digital-Forward or Digital-Native?}}  \n- **Brand Size:** {{Startup, SMB or Enterprise?}}  \n\n## Research Instructions - Phase 1 (Foundation)\n\n### Primary Research Tasks\n\n#### Customer Journey Mapping Research\n- Map all digital and physical touchpoints where target audience interacts with brands in this industry  \n- Document interaction sequences, timing patterns, and contextual factors  \n- Identify common behavioral pathways from awareness to conversion  \n- Focus on measurable behavioral indicators at each touchpoint  \n\n#### Behavioral Signal Inventory\n- Catalog all trackable behavioral signals relevant to this brand type  \n- Include micro-behaviors: click patterns, scroll behaviors, dwell times, interaction frequencies  \n- Document behavioral signal reliability and prediction value  \n- Identify gaps in current behavioral tracking capabilities  \n\n#### Temporal Behavior Pattern Research\n- Analyze when target customers are most active and responsive  \n- Document daily, weekly, monthly, and seasonal behavioral patterns  \n- Identify optimal engagement windows and timing preferences  \n- Map behavioral rhythm variations by audience segment  \n\n### Research Methodology\n- **Primary:** Use RAG database sources prioritized for this brand type and industry  \n- **Validation:** Cross-reference findings from multiple reliable RAG sources  \n- **Backup Protocol:** When RAG sources are insufficient, use web search with these guidelines:  \n  - Search for recent behavioral studies specific to the brand industry/type  \n  - Target authoritative research sources (consulting firms, academic institutions, industry associations)  \n  - Verify findings with multiple sources before inclusion  \n  - Maintain same confidence and quality standards as RAG sources  \n  - Prioritize sources with quantifiable behavioral data  \n  - Focus on recent research (last 18 months preferred)  \n  - Emphasize patterns applicable to automation systems  \n  - Validate behavioral patterns across different studies  \n\n### Data Quality Requirements\n- Seek statistical significance in behavioral patterns  \n- Prioritize research with sample sizes >1,000 participants  \n- Focus on longitudinal studies over snapshot research  \n- Emphasize behavioral causation over correlation where possible  \n\n### Source Diversification Requirements\n- Use minimum 3 different sources per behavioral pattern  \n- When using web search backup, verify findings against RAG sources when possible  \n- Document source type (RAG database vs. web search) in confidence assessment  \n- Flag any insights derived solely from web search for additional validation  \n\n## Delivery Structure\nDeliver exactly 20 insights maximum, formatted as follows:\n\n### TEMPORAL BEHAVIOR PATTERNS (Insights 1-7)\n- **Insight #[1-7]:** [Behavior Type] - [Specific Pattern Name]  \n  [Quantified behavioral observation with specific metrics]  \n  [Contextual trigger, condition, or environmental factor that influences this behavior]  \n  [Specific implication for AI automation systems and brand strategy implementation]  \n  **Source:** [Source Name] | **Confidence:** [HIGH/MEDIUM/LOW] | **Date:** [YYYY-MM]  \n\n### CUSTOMER JOURNEY MAPPI